# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1989-indianapolis-500
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The **Champion Spark Plug 100 Mile an Hour Club** was a group formed to honor drivers who completed the Indianapolis 500 at an average speed of 100 miles per hour or faster.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] It was formed in 1935, and continued to be recognized through 1969.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] It was sponsored by Champion Spark Plugs, and was the brainchild of M.C. deWitt, the company's advertising manager.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] During its heyday, it was considered one of the most prestigious honors in motorsports (the Indy car counterpart to NASCAR's famous Darlington Record Club), and membership was highly sought after by drivers.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] A total of 124 drivers were inducted as members, with 1930 winner Billy Arnold named the club's first member.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The first driver to complete the Indianapolis 500 at an average speed of 100 mph was Pete DePaolo in 1925.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] However, Norman Batten drove 21 laps of relief (laps 106–127) while DePaolo had his hands bandaged due to blisters and bruises.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Thus DePaolo did not accomplish the feat solo.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Five years later in 1930, Billy Arnold won the race with an average speed of 100.488 mph.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] He was the second driver to complete the race in under five hours, but the first ever to do so without relief help.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1934, M.C. deWitt, the advertising manager for Champion, had a conversation with driver Dave Evans.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Evans had finished 6th in the 1934 Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In doing so, Evans had become the twelfth driver in history to complete the full 500 miles solo, at an average speed of over 100 mph.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Immediately deWitt envisioned an idea to create an honorary "club" for the drivers who had accomplished the noteworthy feat.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1935, the **Champion Spark Plugs 100 mph Club** was born.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The inaugural class would consist of the 12 drivers who had accomplished the feat thus far.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The first member retroactively being Billy Arnold, along with Fred Frame, Howdy Wilcox II, Cliff Bergere, Bob Carey, Russ Snowberger, Louis Meyer, Chet Gardner, Wilbur Shaw, Lou Moore, Stubby Stubblefield, and Dave Evans.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] An annual banquet would be held in the drivers' honor, and each inductee would receive a leather jacket.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Carey and Stubblefield were deceased, and Arnold did not attend, but all of the other nine living members were present at the first banquet.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The requirements to qualify for the 100 mph Club were fairly straightforward.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] A driver was required to complete the Indianapolis 500 at an average speed of 100 mph or faster, driving the entire race without any relief help.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] It was permissible to be accompanied by a riding mechanic.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] However, the period in which riding mechanics were utilized at Indianapolis overlapped only briefly from when the club was formed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The 100 mph average speed equated to finishing the race in five hours or less.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The driver was not required to win the race, but a strict requirement was to complete the full 500 miles (200 laps).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Rain-shortened races, or drivers that were flagged off the track before completing all 200 laps (even if their average speed was over 100 mph at the time) would not qualify.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Drivers were inducted for lifetime memberships, but drivers were separately honored each time they accomplished the feat.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Many drivers broke the 100 mph barrier multiple times during the career.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Ted Horn accomplished the feat a record total of eight times in his career.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Each subsequent membership was rewarded with being seated at the head table during the next annual banquet.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Prior to the 1960s, the drivers were permitted ample time to complete the full 500 mile distance, even if it meant remaining on the track for several minutes or over an hour after the winner crossed the finish line.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In the very early years, completing the full 500 miles was even a requirement to receive any prize money.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] For a time, it was the norm for officials to wait until at least 10-12 cars completed the 500 miles before waving the cars off the track.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] However, that was not a hard-and-fast rule.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Officials often just used judgement to decide when it prudent to stop.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] A total of 16 cars went the distance in 1959, while only five did so in 1938.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1940, only the top three were permitted to finish, due to a rain shower.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The honor of joining the prestigious 100 mph Club was considered motivation to continue racing, even if the chance to win the race had already gone away.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In most cases, several cars would complete the distance, and numerous drivers might be added to the Club annually.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Around 1954, Champion formed as part of their public relations efforts, a Driver's education program geared towards teenagers and young adults.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The Champion Highway Safety Program traveled around the country giving presentations at high schools and military bases about driving safety tips.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] For many years, a team of drivers from the 100 mph Club were used to give the lectures, and some were used in Educational films.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The lectures were popular and well-received, and were usually sponsored by a local newspaper or radio station.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The appearances were also used as promotional tool for automobile racing, and offered the drivers work during the off-season.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1964, when the race started airing live on MCA closed-circuit television, the rules were changed which limited the time drivers were allotted to finish the race once the winner crossed the finish line.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Roughly five minutes were allowed for the other cars on the track to complete the 200 laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] This had the effect of substantially limiting the chances of joining the 100 mph Club, and only a handful of drivers earned the honor after 1964.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Also perhaps contributing to the club's demise was the evolving times.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] By the mid-1960s, speeds at Indy had risen considerably since the club's formation - and were poised to rise substantially over the next few years.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Covering the full 500 miles at an average speed of 100 mph was not considered a noteworthy accomplishment any longer.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Most winners were finishing the race with as much as an hour and a half to spare to fulfill the 100 mph Club's qualifications.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Apropos to that, membership in the drivers' eyes was still highly coveted.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1964, rival spark plug manufacturer Autolite created the "Pacemakers Club," which recognized drivers who had led at least one lap during the Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] It began to rise in stature and popularity, and became a more period-relevant "club" associated with the Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In its favor, it was not linked to changes in equipment, conditions, or perceived obsolete speed milestones.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Likewise, it was not adverse to rain-shortened races, and drivers conceivably could still join the "club" despite dropping out of the race - i.e., if he had led laps prior to dropping out.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] During the 1969 race, no new members were inducted into the 100 mph Club, since all four drivers who completed the 500 miles that year were already part of the club.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1970, Dick McGeorge, Champion's public relations representative, retired from his position.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] McGeorge was considered the key fixture in organizing the club, dating back to 1946.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] He died in 1971, and the 100 mph Club quietly folded.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In retrospect, the 1968 inductees (led by race winner Bobby Unser) would be the final names added to the membership.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] One of the more notable omissions from the 100 mph Club was Al Unser Sr.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] He first arrived at Indianapolis in 1965, finishing 9th, flagged after 196 laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] He crashed out in 1966, but in 1967, he was running second in the waning laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Foyt was coming out of turn four to take the checkered flag, a crash occurred on the front stretch.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Foyt weaved his way through the wreck to win, but officials immediately thereafter put out the red flag to stop the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Al Unser was about a lap and a half away from the finish line when he was flagged off and was officially credited with only 198 laps in the final scoring.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] His brother Bobby won, and incidentally joined the 100 mph Club for himself.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Al Unser missed the 1969 race due to a broken leg suffered in a motorcycle crash earlier in the month.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] In 1970, he came back to win the race in dominating fashion.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] His average speed of 155.749 mph was well over the requirement to be invited into the club, and he was expected by all to be honored as the next member.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] However, after McGeorge's retirement, and subsequent passing, the 1971 banquet never happened.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] The club was quietly abandoned and membership was closed without Al Unser ever being officially inducted.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Incidentally, following the demise of the 100 mph Club, Al Unser would go on to complete the full 500 miles seven times (including four wins), all at better than a 100 mph average.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] From 1970 to 2016, a total of 108 additional drivers have unofficially joined the 100 mph Club.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] A total of 33 drivers have joined the very exclusive "185 mph Club".
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] They are led by Tony Kanaan, who won the fastest 500 in 2013.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Two additional drivers, Rick Mears and Michael Andretti, managed to break the 175 mph barrier from the 1991 race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] During the late 1980s and early 1990s, a separate award was created called the **Marlboro 500 Mile Club**.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/100-mph-club] Sponsored by Marlboro, it was a cash prize of $75,000 split amongst the drivers who completed the full 500 miles each year.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The **1911 International 500-Mile Sweepstakes Race** was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Tuesday, May 30, 1911.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] It was the inaugural running of the Indianapolis 500, which is one of the most prestigious automobile races in the world.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Ray Harroun, an engineer with the Marmon Motor Car Company, came out of retirement to drive, and won the inaugural event before re-retiring for good in the winner's circle.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Over the previous two seasons (1909 and 1910), the Speedway had scheduled numerous smaller races during a series of meets over the two years.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In a departure from that policy, for 1911 the management decided to instead schedule a single, large-scale event attracting widespread attention from both American and European racing teams and manufacturers.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] It proved to be a successful event, immediately establishing itself as both the premier motorsports competition in the U.S. and one of the most prestigious in the world.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The race was sanctioned by the AAA Contest Board, and was part of the 1911 season of races.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In an era of two-man cars – consisting of a driver accompanied by a riding mechanic – Ray Harroun famously drove the race solo.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In the days leading up to the race, fellow competitors complained about Harroun's ability to see other cars around him at speed (that duty was typically performed by the riding mechanic).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In an effort to assuage the concerns, Harroun famously affixed a rearview mirror to his machine.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] It is believed to be the first rearview mirror mounted on a racing car, although Harroun himself claimed he got the idea from seeing a mirror used for a similar purpose on a horse-drawn vehicle in 1904.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Harroun also claimed that the mirror vibrated constantly due to the rough brick surface, and it was rendered largely useless.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Nevertheless, Harroun led 88 laps (of 200), running near the front nearly all day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] He executed a preplanned strategy of driving a steady 75 mph pace to reduce his tire wear.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Around the halfway mark, he was briefly relieved by Cyrus Patschke for approximately 35 laps, but got back into the car, and drove to victory by a margin of approximately 1 minute and 42 seconds.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The marathon race was completed in 6 hours and 42 minutes in front of a crowd of over 85,000 spectators.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] A total of twelve cars completed the 500-mile distance, while 12 of the 40 cars dropped out due to crashes or mechanical failures.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] One participant, Sam Dickson (the riding mechanic for Arthur Greiner) was fatally injured after a crash on lap 12.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The 1910 racing season at Indianapolis Motor Speedway began well, with an estimated 60,000 spectators for the 200 mi (320 km) Wheeler-Schebler Trophy on Memorial Day, won by Ray Harroun.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] By the next day, Tuesday, September 6, 1910, local newspapers had already heard rumors of the decision, and reported that the four partners would likely soon choose to concentrate on a singular, major event for 1911.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The endurance event was favored by several manufacturers, but debate soon proceeded as to what would be most beneficial to the spectators as well as the participants.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] While a 24-hour race would be possible on a technical level despite its extreme nature, all agreed that potential ticket-buyers would inevitably depart the grounds well before its conclusion.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The management decided that the ideal "race window" would be from 10 a.m. local time until late afternoon.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] This would allow spectators adequate time to arrive before the start, stay for the entire race, and return home before sundown.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] To fit in that timeframe, that translated to a race distance of 300 to 500 miles (480 to 800 km).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] With total purse estimates ranging upwards of $30,000, the race winner could expect to take home as much as $12,000, the equivalent of over $400,000 in 2026 dollars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In choices for a specific date to hold the race, Memorial Day, already the occasion of the largest previous attendance, was always foremost.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The Independence Day (July 4) date was rejected, as numerous other events such as parades, picnics, and other celebrations already captured the attention of would-be spectators.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Scheduling the race on a Saturday (of a non-holiday weekend) during the summer was also eschewed, since many people – especially in the farming business – worked on Saturdays.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Business associate Lem Trotter informed the Speedway owners that Memorial Day coincided with the completion of a late-spring agricultural practice known as "haying," after which the farmers acquired an effective two-week break.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] While the intention, Trotter argued, would certainly be to draw from far more than just the local farming community, simple business sense called for as little interference as possible with the regional economy.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] That such an opportunity to avoid a conflict of interest fell on a major national holiday sealed the decision: within two days, formal announcement was made of a 500-mile (800 km), marathon-distance motor race, to be held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, May 30, 1911.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] As desired and expected, news of a contest of such distance evoked enthusiasm both within and without the motorsport community.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Newspaper and trade magazine articles used superlatives for the challenges expected to soon face both drivers and engineers.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Interest, however, was far from dampened, with entry blanks distributed over the course of the following month quickly returning filled, the first of which being an automobile built by the J.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Case Threshing Machine Company of Racine, Wisconsin, to be driven by Lewis Strang.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] By May 1, 1911, the final day for entry filing, a high total of some 46 cars had been nominated to compete.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] May 1 also marked the beginning of a long tradition of the opening of the Speedway, on the first day of the month of the race, to free practice on the circuit during daylight hours by any and all participants.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Ultimately, of the full forty-six entries originally submitted, only the two cars of the Falcar team from Moline, Illinois failed to appear, due to an inability to acquire critical chassis pieces.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] To further refine the entry list as the date of the race approached, a qualification system was implemented whereby each car would be required to demonstrate a sufficiently competitive pace.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In reality, no records of the sessions were kept at all, let alone publicized, with the sole objective being the confirmation of each car's capability to achieve the minimum speed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Also in contrast to later eras, both the starting order and the car numbering of the participants were determined not by respective speeds or previous seasonal point totals, but by entry date, with the Strang-driven Case entry being assigned #1 in the first starting position.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The largest racing purse offered to date, $27,550, drew 46 entries from the United States and Europe, from which 40 qualified by sustaining 75 mph (121 km/h) along the quarter mile-long main straight.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Grid positions were determined by date of filing of official entry forms, rather than speed, a difference from the contemporary European practice of lottery.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Entries were prescribed by rules to have a minimum weight of 2,300 lb (1,043 kg) and a maximum engine size of 600 cubic inches (9.83 litres) displacement.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The 40 cars lined up five to a row, except for the first and last.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In the first row, the Stoddard-Dayton pace car was situated on the inside (driven by IMS owner Carl Fisher), with four competitors cars rounding out the row.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Rows 2-8 had five cars each, while the final row had only one car in it.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Fisher's use of the Stoddard-Dayton is believed to constitute the first use of such a vehicle, for the first known mass rolling start of an automobile race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] At some point before the race, Bert Adams was denied a license by the AAA Contest Board - Adams was replaced as driver of the McFarlan by his riding mechanic, Mel Marquette.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] On lap 12 tragedy would strike as Sam Dickson (the riding mechanic for Arthur Greiner) was the first person killed in history during the Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] One of the front wheels came off the American Simplex car Greiner was driving, causing him to lose control and both men to be thrown from the car.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] While Greiner escaped with a broken arm, Dickson flew into a fence 20 feet (6.1 m) from the car.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Reports state that Dickson was killed instantly, although the crowd evidently swarmed around the body, requiring the state militia who were acting as security at the event to use their guns as clubs to clear a path for the attending doctors.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Others faltered during the marathon event, 14 cars fell out of the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Harroun, relieved by Cyrus Patschke for 35 laps (87.5 miles / 140.82 km), led 88 of the 200 laps, the most among the race's seven leaders, for a race-average speed of 74.602 mph (120.060 km/h) in a total time of 6:42:08 for the 500-mile (804.67 km) distance to win.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] During the midpoint of the second half of the race, Harroun and Lozier driver Ralph Mulford had fought an intense duel, with Harroun holding a small advantage near the 340 mile (550 kilometer) mark, whereupon one of the Wasp's tires failed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Harroun's forced stop allowed Mulford to move to the front, before Mulford also pitted for new rubber.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] After Mulford came back onto the track, Harroun was scored in the lead with a 1-minute 48 second advantage, and victory.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] After the race, and collection of $10,000 for first place, Harroun returned to the position he had taken at the end of the 1910 racing season: retirement.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Upon Harroun's declared victory, second-place finisher Mulford supposedly protested, contending he had lapped Harroun when the Marmon limped in on the torn tire, an argument appearing plausible to some, due to an accident disrupting the official timing and scoring stand at nearly the same time.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] However, race officials were quick to note Mulford's subsequent pit stop forced the Lozier crew to spend several minutes themselves changing a tire which stuck to the wheel hub; Mulford's protest was thus denied.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] According to track historian Donald Davidson, no protests were filed at the end of the race and Mulford offered congratulations to Harroun in the *Detroit Free Press* newspaper on June 4.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Davidson has also pointed out that Mulford was reported by contemporary publications to have changed 14 tires during the course of the race, including one from a blown tire in turn one.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Changing tires at the time was a lengthy and painstaking process, as the wheels were typically not removable.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Tires had to be pried off of the rims, remounted, and inflated - all using hand tools, and in the precarious confines of the primitive pit stalls.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Mulford himself even understood and admitted that he lost at least 14 minutes of track position due to his numerous pit stops.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] After blowing the tire on turn one, Mulford had to limp around the track for almost an entire lap, and subsequently bent the rim.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] That necessitated an even longer pit stop at that juncture to hammer out the damage.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] The accounts from the newspapers claim that Harroun changed only four tires all day during only three pit stops.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Harroun's team changed the right rear tire three times, and one other unspecified tire.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Harroun's shorter elapsed time in the pits is alone considered sufficient to more than overcome any track position advantage Mulford might have been thought to have.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] But the undermining evidence to support Harroun as the rightful winner was the team strategy to run a constant 75 mph pace, regardless of position, in order to save tire wear.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] During the 1910 Wheeler-Schebler Trophy Race, as well as during test runs in May 1911, Harroun discovered that by merely running a constant 75 mph pace instead of an 80 mph (or faster) pace, he would substantially reduce his tire wear and increase tire life.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Davidson contends that Mulford did not make serious claims to victory later in life, as some have suggested.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] And in fact the controversy itself did not begin to inflame until decades after the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Likewise, internet-based urban legends, and a book published in 2011, have fueled the controversy.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] It is also possible that Mulford's statements in the *Detroit Free Press* interview were misunderstood or purposely misconstrued.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] While giving full credit to Harroun for winning the race, Mulford did for himself claim the world record for 500 miles driven solo (Harroun had relief help from Cyrus Patschke).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] He also made the largely inconsequential claim that minus the stoppage time needed for pit stops (over 14 minutes), he likely completed the 500 miles (running time only) in less elapsed time than Harroun & Patschke.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Entries were required to maintain an excess of 75 mph (121 km/h) over a quarter-mile distance to qualify.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] However, the starting grid determined by order of entry date.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] No qualification times or speeds were recorded, only pass or fail.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Total laps completed for finishing positions 13th through 26th are unofficial.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Official laps counts were published only for cars that completed all 200 laps (500 miles), and for cars which dropped out.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] All other cars running at the finish were simply listed as "Flagged".
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Some accounts attribute this to a crash that occurred during the race which disrupted the timing and scoring stand for several minutes.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] Following the race, the scoring serials were reviewed and revised multiple times, then the scoring records were subsequently destroyed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] In 1999, historian and statistician Phil Harms published a revised box score for the 1911 Indianapolis 500 at Motorsport.com which included lap counts for all cars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1911-indianapolis-500] According to Harms, the lap totals for positions 13th–26th were "estimated based upon lap time charts".
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] The **1912 Indianapolis 500-Mile Race**, or **International 500-Mile Sweepstakes Race**, the second such race in history, was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Thursday, May 30, 1912.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Indiana-born driver Joe Dawson won the race, leading only the final two laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Ralph DePalma dominated the race, leading 196 of the 200 laps, and pulling out to an over 5-lap lead.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] But with just over two laps to go, his car failed with a broken connecting rod.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] In the aftermath of victory by Ray Harroun in the single-seat Marmon "Wasp" in the first 500-Mile Race the year before, new rules made the presence of riding mechanics mandatory; maximum engine size remained 600 cubic inches (9.83 liters) displacement.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] At $50,000, the race purse was nearly double that of 1911.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Out of 29 original entries, 24 qualified for the race by sustaining a speed faster than a minimum of 75 mph (120.7 km/h) for a full lap, an increase from the quarter-mile qualifying distance of the inaugural year.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] David Bruce-Brown was fastest at 88.45 mph (142.35 km/h), but starting positions were again determined by entry date.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Lining up five cars to the first four rows and four to a fifth, a change from the previous year's starting method was movement of the pace car, a Stutz, from the inside of the first row to out in front of the field.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Upon wave of the then-red starting flag, Teddy Tetzlaff took the lead in a Fiat from the third starting position in the center of the first row, and lead for the first two laps before being overtaken by the grey # 4 Mercedes of Ralph DePalma.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] DePalma's domination of most of the event was total, as he built an eventual five-and-a-half lap, eleven-minute advantage over second, and lead uncontested for the next 194 laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] On lap 87, DePalma led his 85th lap and became the all-time Indianapolis 500 lap leader with 89 laps led (he led 4 laps in the 1911 race), a title he would hold until lap 200 of the 1987 race, 75 years later.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] But at the beginning of lap 197, as his Mercedes began misfiring, and slowed on the main stretch at the conclusion of the lap.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Nursed through the 198th lap by DePalma at reduced speed, the car finally lost all power at the end of the backstretch on lap 199, as a broken connecting rod tore a hole in the crankcase.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Finishing more than ten minutes ahead of newly-second place Tetzlaff, Dawson completed another two laps for good measure upon fear of a scoring miscue.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Dawson's run in the American-manufactured, four-cylinder National, with a winning time of 6:21:06 and averaging 78.719 mph (126.686 km/h), was twenty-one minutes two seconds faster than the previous 1911 record; The National team garnered $20,000 and additional contingency awards.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Throughout the remainder of the field, only the top ten finishers earned prize money, rules stipulating all entries complete the 500 miles (800 km) to collect.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] Entries were required to complete one lap in excess of 75 mph in order to qualify.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1912-indianapolis-500] However, starting grid was determined by order of entry date.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] The **Third International 500-Mile Sweepstakes Race** was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Friday, May 30, 1913.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Frenchman Jules Goux became the first foreign-born, and first European winner of the Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] His margin of victory of 13 minutes, 8 seconds (approximately 7 laps) over second place Spencer Wishart still stands, as of 2026, as the largest margin of victory in Indianapolis 500 history.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] After the entries in the first two years of the Indianapolis 500 had been almost exclusively American, 1913 saw six drivers travel to the United States from Europe to enter, likely attracted by the impressive $20,000 first prize (equivalent to $651,515 in 2025).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] A total of 27 cars would meet the 75 mile per hour qualifying speed, led by Jack Tower at 88.230 mph.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] The starting grid was determined by a random draw of names, and Caleb Bragg would be given the pole.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Tower's car turned over on the southwest turn on lap 51, causing him to sustain a broken leg and his riding mechanic, Lee Dunning, to break three ribs.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Bob Burman started the race as the favorite, and led 41 laps early, before his car caught fire on lap 55.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Burman was able to repair his car and continue, however continuing problems led to several more stops and a replacement driver, who brought the car home in eleventh (unfortunately only the top ten finishers received prize money).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] French-born Jules Goux, driving a car owned and manufactured by Peugeot (where his father was the factory Supervisor) would lead the race on four occasions.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Bob Evans dueled with Goux, leading laps 125–135, but would be forced out of the race on lap 158 due to a mechanical problem.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Goux would dominate the remainder of the race, leading 138 laps en route to a victory of a more than 13 minute margin, making him the first non-American winner of the 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] The car contained a four-cylinder dual overhead camshaft engine, which would serve as a model for many future entries.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Goux would state after the race that his manager forced him to stay below the car's top speed, feeling the lead was safe.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Spencer Wishart was the top finishing American in second, while two of the other European cars would finish fourth and fifth.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Rules at the time required the top ten drivers to finish the full 500 miles to receive prize money.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] This led to an interesting sight for spectators who remained after Goux's finish.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Charlie Merz, in contention for second place, would have his car catch fire towards the end of lap 199.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Merz, not wishing to surrender the prize money, drove the final lap on fire, while Harry Martin, his riding mechanic, crawled out on top of the hood of the still moving car to beat at the flames and release the straps that held the engine cover to allow the fire to be extinguished faster.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Martin would unfortunately be killed while helping test a car on the speedway less than two months later.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Urban legends claim that race winner Jules Goux consumed "six bottles of champagne" en route to victory.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] However, that claim is believed to be exaggerated.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Instead, during Goux's six pit stops, only four bottles (each 4⁄5 pint) were shared between himself and his riding mechanic Emil Begin, with each taking some sips, but likely not enough to become intoxicated.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Other swigs were spit out using the champagne as a mouthwash.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] It was a hot day, and given the punishing conditions, during his first pit stop Goux was quoted as saying *"Rustle me a pint of wine or I'll blow"* After the race, in victory lane, Goux stated *"The heat was terrible.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] I suffered and but for the wine, I should have been unable to drive this race."* In subsequent years, AAA officials banned the consumption of alcohol during competition.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] However, starting positions were determined by blind draw held the night preceding the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Note: Several sources claim Zuccarelli's entry to have carried the numerical designation #15.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1913-indianapolis-500] Photographs taken of entries qualified for the 1913 race, however, exhibit #45 prominently displayed on the Peugeot's front-facing engine grill.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The **4th International 500-Mile Sweepstakes Race** was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Saturday, May 30, 1914.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] René Thomas was the race winner, accompanied by riding mechanic Robert Laly.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The Indianapolis Motor Speedway opened in 1909, and the first motorsport event at the track, a series of motorcycle races, was held in August of that year.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] A series of automobile races were held in 1909, but concerns were raised about the condition of the course after numerous accidents, including a fatality.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The track was re-paved at a high-cost to Carl G.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Fisher and the Indianapolis Motor Speedway Corporation, and further series of races took place in 1910.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Fisher was worried about the dwindling attendances at these races, and decided to establish a 500-mile race; double the furthest distance of any previous race at the track.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] He went on to announce that the track would host no other races during the year, and that the prize for first place would be $25,000: more than 10 times higher than any other race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Fisher's plans paid off, and at the 1911 Indianapolis 500, the inaugural event, newspapers reported that in excess of 80,000 people attended the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Each of the first two races were won by Americans; Ray Harroun in 1911 and Joe Dawson in 1912.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] In 1913, the large prize-fund attracted European teams and racers, and the race was won by Jules Goux in a Peugeot.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] During the 1913 race, Jules Goux and his riding mechanic had drunk 4⁄5 pints of champagne, during each of his pit stops.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] For 1914, the consumption of alcohol during the race was banned.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Riding mechanics were mandatory for the 1914 race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The maximum engine size remained unchanged at 450 cubic inches (7,400 cc) of engine displacement.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] There were 45 entrants for the race, but only the quickest 30 drivers during the elimination trials would qualify for the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The first day of trials was completed on the Monday before the race, May 25.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Caleb Bragg set the fastest official time on the first day, recording 1:36.8, though it was reckoned that Howdy Wilcox went quicker, but his time was not officially recorded.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Ralph DePalma, a crowd favorite, struggled in his Mercedes and could only manage a time of 1:47.4, slower than the 1:45 that it was predicted drivers would have to beat in order to qualify.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Only fifteen of the drivers ran on the first day, and they continued with two sessions on Tuesday.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] On the second day, three drivers set record times around the Speedway: first the 1912 winner, Joe Dawson, set an unofficial lap time of 1:34.8.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Later in the day Teddy Tetzlaff completed a lap in 1:33.4, while Jules Goux finished the day as the fastest driver, with a time of 1:31.7.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Tetzlaff's lap was completed in a Maxwell which was fuelled with a 50:50 mix of gasoline and kerosene; the other Maxwell, driven by Billy Carlson, set a time of 1:36.6 fuelled by a combination of kerosene and lubricating oil, with no gasoline.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Ray Harroun, who had won the inaugural Indianapolis 500 in 1911, designed the Maxwell car, and was given $10,000 (equivalent to $321,000 in 2025) by the company's president as a reward for the cars qualifying with sub-1:37 times.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] By the end of the second day, 21 drivers had completed speed trials, and all but DePalma and Eddie Pullen had times below 1:45.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Hughie Hughes's car suffered a broken crank case, preventing him from being able to set a qualifying time.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] On the final day of the trials, DePalma managed to make significant improvements in his Mercedes, and qualified with the twentieth fastest time overall, in 1:42.12.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Georges Boillot set the overall fastest time, edging out his teammate Goux by completing a lap in 1:30.13, exceeding 125 miles per hour (201 km/h) along the straights.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The slowest of the thirty qualifiers was Harry Grant in a Sunbeam, with a lap time of 1:44.09.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] After the rigors of the elimination trials, DePalma withdrew from the race, claiming that his car had been vibrating so heavily that his engine would not survive the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] His place was taken by Ray Gilhooley in the Italian-built Isotta car.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Gilhooley was known as a fearless, and sometimes erratic, driver who was feared by his peers, as they considered him unpredictable.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] DePalma claimed that he had twice seen Gilhooley "tear through a wooden fence at full tilt" on occasions when Gilhooley risked overtakes on dangerous corners.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The bookmakers made the 1913 race winner, Goux, the favorite, followed by his Peugeot teammate Boillot.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Although the Frenchmen were accepted to be driving the quickest cars, there was some belief in the American press that their English tires might not be as durable as American tires, which could improve the chances of the American drivers.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The starting lineup for the race was determined by random draw the night before the race amongst the qualified drivers.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Frenchman Jean Chassagne drew pole position, while Teddy Tetzlaff and Howdy Wilcox completed the front row.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Wilcox led the first lap of the race, but the European drivers dominated the day, with five of the top six finishing positions going to them.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] René Thomas, driving a French-made Delage, led 102 laps en route to victory, setting a new record average speed of 82.47 mph (132.72 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Belgian Arthur Duray finished second after leading 77 laps, roughly 6 minutes 38 seconds behind Thomas.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] Barney Oldfield finished as the highest place American in fifth placed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1914-indianapolis-500] The starting grid was determined by a random draw the night before the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] The **5th International 500-Mile Sweepstakes Race** was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Monday, May 31, 1915.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] The traditional race date of May 30 fell on a Sunday, but race organizers declined to schedule the race for Sunday.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] The race was set for Saturday May 29, but heavy rains in the days leading up to the race flooded the grounds and made some roads leading to the track impassible.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] Officials decided to postpone the race until Monday May 31 in order to allow the grounds to dry out.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] Speedway management would maintain their policy to not race on Sundays until 1974.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] After a loss in 1912, Ralph DePalma succeeded in victory for 1915.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1915-indianapolis-500] DePalma was accompanied by riding mechanic Louis Fountaine.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] The **6th International 300-Mile Sweepstakes Race** was the sixth running of the Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] It was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Tuesday, May 30, 1916.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] The management scheduled the race for 120 laps, 300 miles (480 km), the only Indianapolis 500 scheduled for less than 500 miles (800 km).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Although the common belief is that the race distance was changed due to the onset of World War I, it was in fact Speedway management that changed the distance in an attempt to make the race shorter and more appealing to fans.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Despite the one-time altered distance, the race is still considered part of the continuous lineage of the Memorial Day classic, known as the Indianapolis 500.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Seven of the cars were entered by the Speedway or its owners, in order to ensure a strong field during the war.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Despite the promoter's entries, the field consisted of only 21 cars, the smallest in Indy history.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] 1915 winner Ralph DePalma withheld his entry for 1916, demanding $5,000 in appearance money from Speedway management.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Carl Fisher refused to accede to the demand, and DePalma's subsequent entry blank, filed after the deadline, was rejected.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Eddie Rickenbacker took the lead at the start, and led the first nine laps until dropping out with steering problems.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Dario Resta led 103 of the 120 laps, and claimed the victory.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Resta was accompanied by riding mechanic Bob Dahnke.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Three months after the 1916 race, on the weekend after Labor Day, the Speedway held a second event, with three short races as the Harvest Auto Racing Classic.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] The 1917 race was scheduled to return to 500 miles, but a dispute with the local hoteliers and the escalation of World War I intervened.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] On March 23, 1917, Speedway management cancelled the 1917 Indianapolis 500, and halted racing at the facility for both 1917 and 1918.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] The track was offered as a landing strip and maintenance/refueling station for military aircraft traveling between Wilbur Wright Field and Chanute Air Force Base.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] It was referred to as the Speedway Aviation Repair Depot, and the 821st Aero Repair Squadron was stationed there.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] In addition, several experimental aircraft were tested at the grounds.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] At least one test pilot was fatally injured in a plane crash at the track.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] No racing of any kind took place at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in 1917–1918.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] Likewise, the National Championship was suspended in both 1917 and 1918.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] There were, however, AAA races (non-championship races) conducted during the war years at other tracks.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] On Memorial Day 1917, a 250-mile race was held at Cincinnati.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1916-indianapolis-500] The Indianapolis 500 resumed after the war in 1919.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The **73rd Indianapolis 500** was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in Speedway, Indiana on Sunday, May 28, 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The race was won by Emerson Fittipaldi, a two-time Formula One World Drivers' Champion.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Fittipaldi became the first Indy 500 winner from Brazil, the first foreign-born winner of the race since Mario Andretti in 1969, and the first non-American winner since Graham Hill in 1966.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Though Fittipaldi started on the front row and dominated much of the race, he found himself running second in the waning laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Michael Andretti passed Fittipaldi for the lead on lap 154, then led until his engine blew.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Al Unser Jr. moved up to second, but trailed Fittipaldi by a big margin.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Gambling on fuel mileage, Unser caught up to Fittipaldi after a fortuitous caution period on lap 181, and subsequently took the lead on lap 196.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On the 199th lap, Unser was leading Fittipaldi, at which time the two leaders encountered slower traffic.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Down the backstretch, Unser and Fittipaldi weaved through the slower cars, then Fittipaldi dived underneath going into turn three.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The two cars touched wheels, and Unser spun out, crashing into the outside retaining wall.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Fittipaldi completed the final lap under caution behind the pace car to score his first of two Indy 500 victories.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser was uninjured, and despite the crash, was still credited with second place.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Fittipaldi received $1,001,600 in prize money, the first time an Indianapolis 500 winner received over one million dollars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] After dominating the previous year's race, all three cars of the Penske team failed to finish the race in 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rick Mears won the pole position, his record fifth Indy pole, and Al Unser Sr. qualified second.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Danny Sullivan, however, suffered a broken arm in a practice crash, and had to qualify a backup car on the second weekend of time trials, so he started 26th.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mechanical failures sidelined all three cars on race day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] It was the only year in the decade of the 1980s, and the first time since 1976, that the Penske team failed to score a top five finish.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Apropos to that, Fittipaldi won the race with a Penske PC-18 chassis, which Patrick Racing had acquired from Penske in a complex and multi-faceted trade deal.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The race was sanctioned by USAC, and was included as part of the 1989 CART PPG Indy Car World Series.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At season's end, Fittipaldi became the fourth driver since 1979 to win the Indy 500 and CART championship in the same season.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The win was also Patrick Racing's third and final Indy victory (1973, 1982, 1989).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Former driver Chip Ganassi, who had become co-owner at Patrick Racing in 1988, enjoyed his first of seven Indy victories (as of 2025) as a car owner or co-owner.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Speedway management resurfaced the entire track with asphalt during the summer of 1988, which would result in higher overall speeds for 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The last time the track had been repaved was in 1976.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The apron at the bottom of the track (typically used for warm-up and cool-down laps, as well as an escape lane for slowing cars), which was previously known to be bumpy, relatively flat, and usually avoided by drivers, was also repaved.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The racing surface was separated from the apron by a painted white line.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The smooth and re-profiled apron was now tempting drivers to dip below the white line in practice and during the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Drivers were starting to treat the apron as an extension of the track width.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] USAC announced penalties would be assessed for driving with four wheels below the white line excessively, other than to make routine passes in heavy traffic.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The rough and bumpy concrete pit lane was also paved over in asphalt and a guardrail was installed to protect the crew members in the sign board area.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The newly paved pit area made egress and ingress to the pits smoother and safer, but also sharply increased entrance and exit speeds, potentially putting crew members at risk.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Within a few years, after a succession of incidents on the Indy car circuit, as well as in NASCAR, pit road speed limits would be implemented to curtail excessive speeding through the pit lane.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In addition, the pneumatic jacks built into the cars were found to be embedding themselves into the soft asphalt of the pit lane.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] This necessitated crews to affix steel plates on the pit lane to accommodate the jacks (a practice that was also later deemed unsafe).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In 1994, this would be finally be solved when the individual pit boxes were resurfaced in concrete.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Goodyear arrived at the track providing both a hard and soft compound tire.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The exclusive tire provider spent the off-season developing new tires that were better-suited to the newly repaved track.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Teams were permitted to run either compound at any time, however, they were required to start the race on the same tires that they used during time trials.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] All teams qualified on the soft compounds, thus all were required to start the race on soft compounds.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Teams electing to switch to hard compound tires for the race could do so on their first pit stop.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Team and driver changes were highlighted by Bobby Rahal's departure from Truesports.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] For 1989, Rahal switched to the Maurice Kranes Kraco Racing Team (A year later, the team would merge with Galles).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rahal, along with Arie Luyendyk at Dick Simon Racing, fielded the new Cosworth DFS "short stroke", and updated version of the mainstay DFV.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] However, Rahal's DFS engine blew during Carburetion Day practice, and for race day the team would have to revert to a previous generation DFX.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rookie Scott Pruett, the IMSA GTO and SCCA Trans-Am champion, moved to the Indy car ranks, and took over the vacated seat at Truesports.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The team would continue to field the Judd powerplant.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] After a noteworthy 6th-place performance in the 1988 race, Jim Crawford was back at King Racing.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Chip Ganassi joined Pat Patrick as co-owner at Patrick Racing for Emerson Fittipaldi's #20 Marlboro entry.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Speculation was emerging that Pat Patrick was planning to phase out his full-time ownership role, perhaps pursue a leadership position in CART, or even retire.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Patrick himself mostly rebuffed the rumors, stating that bringing in Ganassi as an investor was merely a "business decision".
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Meanwhile, team sponsor Marlboro was nearing the end of their contract.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Patrick was still in good standing with Ilmor, and would continue to field the Chevrolet engine.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] A multi-faceted "trade" deal between Patrick Racing and Penske Racing unfolded over a period of about two years, involving sponsors, drivers, and cars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] For 1989, an agreement was reached whereby Marlboro would stay for another season at Patrick and Penske would supply Patrick with two PC-18 chassis for Fittipaldi.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In return, Penske would receive interim Marlboro sponsorship to field a third car for Al Unser Sr. at the three 500-mile races in 1989 (Indianapolis, Michigan, and Pocono).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Newman Haas Racing also made headlines, expanding to a two-car team for 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mario Andretti was joined by his son Michael to form a two-car Andretti effort.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] It was also Michael's first opportunity to compete with the Chevrolet engine.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Michael had previously driven for the Kraco Racing Team.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Alfa Romeo joined the CART series with Alex Morales Motorsports in 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] However, they were not yet ready to compete at Indianapolis.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Their debut would actually come a couple weeks later at Detroit.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] As a result, driver Roberto Guerrero would miss the Indy 500 for the first time since he arrived as a rookie in 1984.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Absent from the race as a driver was Dick Simon, who retired at the end of the 1988 season.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Simon had been a participant at Indy since 1970, but was still entered as owner of Dick Simon Racing.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Only eleven cars took to the track on a cold 45 °F (7 °C) day, which saw snow flurries in the morning and the afternoon.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Arie Luyendyk (213.657 mph (343.848 km/h)) led the speed chart for the day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Practice picked up on Sunday May 7, with 44 cars taking to the track.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Emerson Fittipaldi (221.347 mph (356.223 km/h)) set the fastest lap of practice thus far.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Michael Andretti was also over 220 mph (350 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rick Mears set an all-time unofficial track record at 225.733 mph (363.282 km/h), the first ever practice lap over 225 mph (362 km/h) at the Speedway.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] His teammate Al Unser was close behind at 224.831 mph (361.830 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rookie Steve Butler crashed in turn 4, suffering a broken collarbone, sidelining him for the month.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The speeds were slightly down from Monday, with Al Unser topping the chart at 223.380 mph (359.495 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At 4:11 p.m. on Thursday May 11, Danny Sullivan's car lost the engine cover, causing him to break into a 180° spin in turn three.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The car hit the wall hard with the right side.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Sullivan suffered a mild concussion and a fractured right arm.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Sullivan would be forced to sit out the first weekend of time trials.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] High winds kept the speeds down, with Jim Crawford in a Buick V-6 (221.021 mph (355.699 km/h)) the best lap of the day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rick Mears blistered the track on the final day of practice before time trials.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] His lap of 226.231 mph (364.084 km/h) was the fastest practice lap ever run at the Speedway.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Jim Crawford and Al Unser also topped 225 mph (362 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mears finished the week as the favorite for the pole position.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Pole day was scheduled for Saturday May 13.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rain, however, washed out the entire day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] All time trial activities were postponed until Sunday.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On Sunday May 14, pole day time trials were held.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Per USAC rules at the time, the cars would be allowed one trip through the qualifying draw order, and the pole round would be concluded.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Al Unser Sr. drew first in line, and was the first driver to make an attempt.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser set a track record on all four laps, and put himself on the provisional pole position with a track record run of 223.471 mph (359.642 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] A busy hour of qualifying saw several cars complete runs.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Scott Brayton, Scott Pruett, Bernard Jourdain, Teo Fabi, and Michael Andretti were among those who completed runs.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Foyt followed, and the field was already filled to eleven cars by 1:30 p.m.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The next car out, however, was pole favorite Rick Mears.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mears set a one-lap track record of 224.254 mph (360.902 km/h), and a four-lap record of 223.885 mph (360.308 km/h) to secure the pole position.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Minutes later, it was announced that Michael Andretti's car failed post-qualifying inspection.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] His run was disallowed as the car found to be 4.5 pounds underweight.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] With Mears and Unser Sr. firmly holding the top two spots, the rest of the session focused on which driver would round out the front row in third starting position.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Jim Crawford, in the Buick V-6, set a stock block track record of 221.450 mph (356.389 km/h) to sit in third at 2:40 p.m.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Twenty minutes later, though, Emerson Fittipaldi took to the track, the final car eligible for the pole round.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] His run of 222.329 mph (357.804 km/h) put him on the outside of the front row, and bumped Crawford back to the inside of row two.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] After the pole position round was settled, the "Second Day" of time trials commenced at 3:15 p.m.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Second day qualifiers would line up behind the first day qualifiers.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Michael Andretti re-qualified at 218.774 mph (352.083 km/h) (the 8th fastest car in the field), but was forced to start 22nd as a second-day qualifier.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Andretti complained he could not get to the proper level of turbocharger boost due a possibly malfunctioning pop-off valve, but USAC took no action.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Tom Sneva had an impressive first lap of 223.176 mph (359.167 km/h), but blew his engine before the run was completed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At the end of the day, the field was filled to 26 cars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Practice during the second week was light, with many qualified drivers practicing in back-up cars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Most of the focus was on the non-qualified drivers, and the recovery status of Danny Sullivan.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The Penske Team started preparing a back-up machine for Sullivan, with Geoff Brabham selected to shake the car down.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Danny Sullivan returned to the cockpit on Thursday May 18.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Jim Crawford crashed his already-qualified car in turn 3.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] A suspension piece broke as he entered the turn, and the car spun into the outside wall.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rain washed out practice on "Fast" Friday May 19, the third day overall lost during the month.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On the third day of time trials, Danny Sullivan qualified comfortably at 216.027 mph (347.662 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Sullivan was the fastest car of the day, followed by Kevin Cogan and Rocky Moran.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Two crashes occurred during the day, involving Buddy Lazier and Steve Saleen.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At the end of the third day, the field was filled to 31 cars.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On Bump Day, much of the attention was focused on three-time Indy winner Johnny Rutherford, the biggest name who had not yet qualified.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] As the day opened, Billy Vukovich III (216.698 mph (348.742 km/h)) put his car in the field with an impressive run, ranked 16th-fastest overall.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The second car to qualify was Johnny Rutherford, who completed his run at 213.097 mph (342.946 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Davy Jones (211.475 mph (340.336 km/h)) was the slowest car in the field, and now on the bubble.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] John Paul Jr. bumped Davy Jones out of the field at 12:45 p.m.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Paul was attempting to make a return to Indy after a four-year absence.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] His career was interrupted in 1986 when he was sentenced to five years in prison for his involvement in a drug trafficking ring with his father (John Paul Sr.) and subsequently refused to testify against him.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He served a total of thirty months, being released in October 1988.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Though tentatively in the field, Paul himself was now sitting on the bubble in 33rd at 211.969 mph (341.131 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The track activity went quiet during the heat of the afternoon.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At 3 p.m., Davy Jones returned to the track and bumped his way back into the field with a run at 214.279 mph (344.849 km/h).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At 4:45 p.m., Pancho Carter bumped out Krueger.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At that point, Johnny Rutherford (213.097 mph (342.946 km/h)) had now slipped down to the bubble spot.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rutherford survived three attempts, and clung to the bubble spot nervously over the next hour.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] During that time, he put together a last-minute deal to step into a Foyt back-up car if necessary.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He shook down the car with some practice laps, and appeared to be finding some speed.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] It was the second time in recent years that Rutherford was teaming up with Foyt on Bump Day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In 1984 Rutherford successfully bumped his way into the field with a Foyt backup car in the last ten minutes of time trials.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] With fifteen minutes left in the day, Rich Vogler (213.239 mph (343.175 km/h)) bumped Johnny Rutherford from the field.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rutherford scrambled to get in line, and made it to the front with less than two minutes to spare.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] With the crowd cheering him on, at 5:58 p.m., Rutherford pulled out onto the track for one final attempt.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He had a great warm-up lap of over 217 mph (349 km/h), but just after he took the green flag, his engine blew in turn one.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Seconds later, the 6 o'clock gun went off.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rutherford failed to make the field for only the second time in his career.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rookie Bernard Jourdain held on to the final bubble spot, and the field was set.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The final practice session was held Thursday May 25.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] (217.407 mph) was the fastest driver of the day.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Jim Crawford's car was repaired and returned to the track after his crash the previous week.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Bobby Rahal suffered engine issues, which cut his day short.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The semifinals and finals for the 13th annual Miller Pit Stop Contest were held on Thursday May 25.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The top three race qualifiers and their respective pit crews were automatically eligible: Rick Mears, Al Unser Sr., Emerson Fittipaldi.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Jim Crawford (who qualified 4th) took the empty spot.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Al Unser Jr. secured the fourth and final spot in the contest during preliminaries which were on held on Wednesday May 17.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] (13.618 seconds) defeated Bobby Rahal of KRACO Racing (24.432 seconds).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Rahal suffered a 10-second penalty for running over an air hose.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mario Andretti also participated, but he was disqualified for running through the lights.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On the morning of Thursday May 18, a second round of preliminaries was held.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Teo Fabi (16.286 seconds) was the fastest of the day, but was unable to top Unser Jr.'s time from Wednesday.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Others included: Tom Sneva (17.082 seconds), A.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Foyt (17.257 seconds), John Andretti (23.391 seconds), Pancho Carter (stalled), Michael Andretti (crew disqualified for pushing the car).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] King Racing withdrew from the contest after Jim Crawford crashed the team's primary car on the afternoon of May 18.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In the first semifinal, Al Unser Jr. defeated his father Al Unser Sr..
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The Penske crew was issued two penalties, 10 seconds for running over a hose, and 5 additional seconds for a loose wheel.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mario Andretti defeated Emerson Fittipaldi in a close match in the second semifinal.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In the final round, Al Unser Jr. of Galles Racing and led by chief mechanic Owen Snider, faced Mario Andretti of Newman/Haas Racing, led by chief mechanic Colin Duff.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser defeated Andretti by over 6 seconds.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Andretti was subsequently issued an additional 5-second penalty due to a loose wheel.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] During one of the parade laps, veteran Gary Bettenhausen suffered a broken valve, and coasted to a stop on the mainstretch.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He would be wheeled to the garage area without completing a single lap, and finished 33rd.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At the start, Emerson Fittipaldi jumped to the lead from the outside of the front row.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He pulled out to a sizable lead over the first few laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On the third lap, Kevin Cogan had a spectacular crash at the pit-entrance section of the front straightaway.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] His car made slight contact with the outside wall as he exited turn four, spun to the inside and made heavy contact with the inside pit wall.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The car rebounded into the attenuating barrier at the pit entrance (also breaking the ABC Sports robo camera at the pit road entry), broke in two pieces, and slid on its side through the pits.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The engine completely separated from the remains of the car and came to a stop in the pit area.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The race was dominated by Emerson Fittipaldi for the first 400 miles.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] During that stretch, several contenders retired due to mechanical failures, including all three Penske machines.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Top-five contenders Bobby Rahal, Jim Crawford, and Arie Luyendyk also dropped out of the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Mario Andretti experienced electrical problems, which caused him to lose significant ground to the leader.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Michael Andretti, who had started in the seventh row, had been chasing Fittipaldi the entire race and by the 150-lap mark, he was within sights of the leader.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Meanwhile, Al Unser Jr. remained on the lead lap in third place, despite being lapped earlier in the race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] By this point, the three leaders had significant distance on the fourth place car of Raul Boesel.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] With less than 100 miles to go, Michael Andretti passed Fittipaldi for the lead, but his engine expired a few laps later.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Fittipaldi regained the lead, with Al Unser Jr. second.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The remainder of the field ran at least six laps behind.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] A caution came out on lap 181 when Tero Palmroth lost a wheel in turn four.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Leader Fittipaldi pitted for much-needed fuel, but he nearly stalled his engine as he pulled away.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He lost several seconds on the stop, and was also blocked momentarily by a safety truck as he exited the pit area.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Al Unser Jr. was running a distant second place, but the caution came partly to his advantage.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On the previous rounds of pit stops, Unser Jr. had been experiencing slightly better fuel mileage than Fittipaldi.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The team had been setting Unser up to potentially make it to the finish on one less pit stop than Fittipaldi.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Under this late yellow, the team decided to gamble on track position, and Unser stayed out and did not to pit for fuel.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser emerged just one car behind Fittipaldi.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Team owner Rick Galles made the call not to pit – their fuel calculations were close enough that believed they could make it to the finish.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Their reasoning was that even if Unser ran out of fuel on the final lap, they would still finish no worse than second since third place Raul Boesel was six laps behind.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] When the race restarted on lap 186, Fittipaldi quickly built a 3-second lead while Unser struggled to get around the lapped car of Raul Boesel (3rd place).
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Boesel's car was spewing fluid, and appeared ready to blow.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] After clearing Boesel, Unser began closing dramatically.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] By lap 193 he was directly behind Fittipaldi, and a lap later he nearly touched wheels with him as the two drivers worked around the lapped cars of Derek Daly and Mario Andretti and battled for the lead.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On lap 196, Unser passed Fittipaldi for the lead in turn three and began to pull away.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser's light fuel load made him much faster on the straights but there was still considerable fear he might run out of fuel short of the finish line.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] With two laps to go, Unser approached a line of slower cars consisting of Rocky Moran, Ludwig Heimrath Jr., Bernard Jourdain and John Jones.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The two leaders were able to get around Moran easily in turn one, but Unser was held up behind Heimrath through turn two, allowing Fittipaldi to close in rapidly.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] On the backstretch, Fittipaldi pulled inside Unser, who then cut to the inside to pass Heimrath.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Both cars ran side-by-side down the backstretch, going 3-wide to pass Jourdain on the inside as they entered turn 3.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser remained on the racing line, with Fittipaldi down low on the warm-up apron.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Near the apex of the corner, Fittipaldi's car oversteered and drifted slightly up the track, and the two cars touched wheels.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser spun and crashed hard into the turn three wall, while Fittipaldi recovered from the drift and continued on.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The yellow flag came out for the last lap with Fittpaldi leading, cruising around on his way to certain victory.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Unser emerged from his crashed car unhurt and stepped to the edge of the track to gesticulate at Fittipaldi as he drove by.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] According to Unser, at the last second he reconsidered and gave Fittipaldi a sporting thumbs-up instead, but some viewers interpreted his gesture as a mocking one.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The pace car escorted the field around the final corner, and for the second year in a row, the race finished under caution.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Emerson Fittipaldi took the checkered flag, his first of two Indy 500 victories.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Despite the crash Unser was still credited with second place, having completed four more laps than Boesel in third.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Boesel managed to nurse his failing motor to the checkered flag.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The third place was his best Indy finish, and best finish to-date for Shierson Racing.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Fittipaldi's win was well received by the Indy car community.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Fittipaldi also spoke, in his native Portuguese, a greeting to the people in Brazil in victory lane, to the thunderous roars of the crowd.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Al Unser Jr., after being checked out and released from the track hospital, congratulated his adversary on the win, and rejected theories that Fittipaldi intentionally crashed him in response to their previous year's tangle at the Meadowlands.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The race was carried live on the IMS Radio Network.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Lou Palmer served as the chief announcer for the second and final time.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] It would be Palmer's 32nd and final 500 as part of the radio crew.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] One of the more significant changes involved Howdy Bell, now becoming the "elder statesman" of the crew.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] After many years in turn two, then one year as a pit reporter, Bell revived the backstretch reporting location.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Bell was utilized sparingly, mostly for observations and brief commentary.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The on-air "Statistician" duty was eliminated for 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] This would be Bob Lamey's last year in turn two, and Bob Jenkins' final year as the radio reporter in turn four.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The biggest departure for 1989 was that of Luke Walton, who had joined the crew in 1953.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Walton was a pit reporter from 1953 to 1982.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Then from 1983 to 1988, he reprised his traditional role of introducing the starting command during the pre-race ceremonies; but he did not have an active role during the race itself.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Pit reporter Gary Gerould took over the duty of introducing the starting command, but it would be the final time that was done on the radio broadcast.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Starting in 1990, the radio would instead simulcast the public address system during the pre-race ceremonies.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] This was Gerould's last year on the radio broadcast.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] He would work the television broadcast starting in 1990.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] In addition, Chuck Marlowe switched from pit reporter to the garage area duties.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Three-time Indy 500 winner Johnny Rutherford failed to qualify for the race, and joined the crew on race day as "driver expert".
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Since Rutherford never again qualified for the race (and subsequently retired in 1994), he went on to become a long-time fixture on the broadcast.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The 1989 race began what would be a 14-year run for Rutherford as the resident "driver expert".
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] After the race, during the off-season, the Speedway and Lou Palmer parted ways.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] A new *Voice of the 500* would debut in 1990, along with many other changes.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The race was carried live flag-to-flag coverage in the United States on ABC Sports.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The 1989 race celebrated the 25th year of the Indy 500 on ABC.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Paul Page served as host and play-by-play announcer, accompanied by Bobby Unser and Sam Posey.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] At the start of the race, Unser drove the pace car, and reported live from the car during the pace laps.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Pit reporters Jack Arute and Brian Hammons were joined by Dr.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Jerry Punch, who appeared at Indy for the first time.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The **1988–89 USAC Gold Crown Championship** season consisted of one sanctioned race.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The schedule was based on a split-calendar, beginning in June 1988 and running through May 1989.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Starting in 1981, USAC scaled back their participation in top-level Indy car racing, and ultimately ceased sanctioning races outside of the Indianapolis 500 following their 1983–84 season.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Subsequently, the Gold Crown Championship would consist of only one event annually; the winner of the Indianapolis 500 would be the de facto Gold Crown champion, as it was their lone points-paying event.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] The preeminent national championship season was instead sanctioned by CART, and the Indy 500 paid championship points separately (on a different scale) toward the CART championship as well.
[src:1989-indianapolis-500/1989-indianapolis-500] Emerson Fittipaldi, by virtue of winning the 1989 Indianapolis 500, also won the 1988–89 USAC Championship.
